                       SPACE PROGRAM PROVES THE BIBLE RIGHT

               (Permission has been granted to reprint the following
          report by Mr.  Harold Hill, a consultant in the space program.)

       (Edited by Larry Turnage)

       "I think one  of  the most amazing things that God has for us today,
       happened recently to our astronauts  and  space  scientists at Green
       Belt, Md. They  were  checking  the position of the  sun,  moon  and
       planets with a computer program.

       It's imperative to  know these positions 100 and 1000 years from now
       so we don't have a satellite crash into something later on in one of
       it's orbits. We have to lay out the  orbits  in terms of the life of
       the satellites so that the whole program want bog down."

       "They ran the   computer  measurement  back  and  forth   over   the
       centuries, when suddenly  the  program  came to a halt and sent up a
       'red flag'. There was either something  wrong  with  the information
       fed into the  computer  or  with  the  results  as compared  to  the
       standards. They called  in  the  service department to check it out.
       They said they could find no reason  for  the  problem.  The head of
       operations said, 'What's wrong?'

       Well, they found that there was a day missing in  space  in  elapsed
       time. Everyone scratched  their heads and torn their hair. There was
       no answer!"

       "One of the chaps on the team was  a  Bible  student  and he finally
       remarked, 'You know,  once  when  I  was  in Sunday  School  it  was
       discussed that once in olden times the sun stood still.'

       Well, no one   would   buy  that  but  since  no  other  answer  was
       forthcoming someone finally asked,  'Show  us  where?.'   They got a
       bible and the religious chap went to the book of Joshua,  where they
       found a statement  that 'seemed' to be a pretty ridiculous statement
       for anyone to believe who had any 'common sense.'


